Security groups and cloud networking


What are security groups ?  
= Security groups are virtual firewalls for AWS instances like EC2


 → Security group rules can reference by IP or by security groups ( instances with similar security group)

 → They control inbound and outbound traffic at the instance level ( EC2 instance )
 → Security groups contain  “Allow rules” that for example allow traffic - SSH on port 22 / HHTP on port 80
 → Any traffic not explicitly allowed is denied    so u can block ssh etc 
 → Help secure your AWS resource / service 


Security groups in detail? 

Security groups acting as virtual “firewalls”  on an EC2 instance 

Security Groups regulate things like : 
- Access to PORTS
- Authorised IP ranges = IPv4 & IPv6
- Control inbound / outbound traffic = to and from the EC2 instance  <-> (like preventing it access to the internet )

Best practice to keep security groups as tight as possible 
 → I.e HTTP request ride on top of TCP protocol (connection based protocol ) to ensure it can be access from any IP and listens on port 80 
 →  but SSH request to connect rides on top of TCP protocol and listens on port 22 but can be accessed by a specific IP address (my own )


Security group diagram ?

Your computer ( IP XXX ) authorised port 22  → Security group 1 inbound (Filter IP/Port with rules )  →  SSH into EC2 instance 

EC2 instance  →  (outbound traffic)  →  security group 2 outbound (Filter IP/Port with rules ) → AWS allow outbound to any port (download updates) → WWW (any IP - ANY PORT)

** Best practice- tighten outbound rules for your EC2 instance 


Extra info on security groups ?

→ can be attached to multiple instances 
→ they can be locked down to a region / VPC combination *
→ If traffic is blocked by SG the EC2 won’t see it 

→ Good to maintain one security group for SSH access 
→ if application not available / times out = security group issue 
→if application has “connection refused” = application error / not launched 

→ all inbound traffic is blocked by default 
→ all outbound traffic is authorised by default 


Referencing other security groups of EC2 instances ?

I.e within an ECS Cluster you can have different part of an app as microservices within multiple EC2 instances 

For the EC2 Instances to communicate  
→ you reference the other security groups to be able to receive inbound traffic on a certain port 

EC2 x3 -> port 123 ->  Security group 1,2,3   -> EC2 instance   <->



Important PORTS to know ?

Port 22 = SSH (secure shell) login into linux instance 

Port 21 = FTP ( File transfer protocol) upload files using file share 

Port 22 = SFTP ( secure file transfer protocol) - upload files using Ssh

Port 80 = HTTP access to unsecured websites 

Port 443 = HTTPS - access to secure websites 
 
Port 53 = DNS - for DNS queries and resolving 

3389 RDP ( Remote Desktop protocol ) - login into windows instance 





What are Elastic IP’s 

When you start and strop an EC2 instance it can get assigned another IP address 
= due to AWS allocates IP addresses dynamically 

→ If you need a fixed IP address for security rules , polices , whitelisting or External access = use an Elastic IP 
- It is a PUBLIC IPv4 IP that you own as long as you don’t delete it 

→ But can only attach it to one instance at a time 


When to use an elastic IP ?

→ You can mask the failure of an instance of software with an elastic IP by rapidly remapping the address to another healthy instance 
- But can only have 5 Elastic IP in your account ( unless increased by AWS )

→ Overall AVOID using Elastic IP 
- As they reflect poor architecture diagrams 
- Instead use random public IPv4 addresses and register DNS name to it 

+ use a load balancers and that doesn’t use a public IP **

 ON AWS 

EC2 - Network + security -> elastic IP  ( and then associate it with a running EC2 )



IPv4 vs IPv6 ?


IPv4 → [0-255].[0-255].[0-255].[0-255]
-  is still the most common format used online 
- Allows for 3.7 billion different addresses in the public space 

Public = unique and machine is reachable over internet → must be unique + geo lacated easily 

Private = machine can only reachable on a private network 
- IP must be unique across the private network 
- 2 private networks (different companies) can have the same IPs
- Machines connect to internet using → NAT + internet gateway ( a proxy )
- Only a specific range of IP’s can be used as a private IP  

Client initiates request to public web server -> travels over internet -> request hit public internet gateway -> securely routes to private network whilst shielding everything internal 

IPv6 - is newer and solves problems for the internet of Things (IOT)

